entry.title: [Mac Base VM] Test for region overlap (not equality) in ScopedMacVM unittests
entry.content:
As of macOS 13 on Intel, it appears that Darwin may combine a

requested VM allocation with an existing one. As a result, when we call

vm_region_64 to get info about a requested allocation, the OS may

return a larger region. This caused the unit tests to fail

because they were checking for region equality. This cl modifies

the unit tests to check that the requested region is a subset of

the region returned from vm_region_64.

entry.title: Fix corner case with automatic beacons and ctrl+click.
entry.content:
A prior CL allowed an automatic beacon to be sent when ctrl+clicking on

a link[1]. However, that fix only works as long as the ETLD+1 of the

navigation initiator and page being navigated to are the same. That

means that cross-domain navigations will still not send an automatic

beacon from a ctrl+click. This happens because the navigation request's

commit params' `was_activated` boolean is only set to true if the ETLD+1

of the navigation destination and initiator are the same[2].



This CL instead looks at the navigation request's common params'

`has_user_gesture` variable to check if there was user activation when

the link was clicked. This replaces the transient user activation check

on the initiator directly + the `was_activated` check that was being

used before.



This CL also updates the ctrl+click automatic beacon WPT to perform a

navigation to a page with a different ETLD+1 to explicitly check this

corner case, as well as checks middle click navigations.



[1]https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4670828

[2]https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/renderer_host/navigation_request.cc;l=443;drc=68f3441bbaeef0a0f464de54ef34baeef1d6ad98

entry.title: [AsyncTask] Clear interrupt at the end of task if set
entry.content:
AsyncTask#cancel calls FutureTask#cancel which may interrupt the

executing background thread. If the background thread never checks the

interrupt as part of its AsyncTask#doInBackground the interrupt will not

be cleared.



Address this by clearing the interrupt at the last possible moment in

FutureTask#run. This is late enough that the interrupt can no longer

occur and will ensure the thread is in a clean state for re-use.

This CL broadcasts HidePopup() in ContentAutofillRouter rather than

unicasting it to the last-queried ContentAutofillDriver.



This is another step to eliminate the tracking the last-queried

ContentAutofillDrivers in ContentAutofillRouter, which is the most

complicated bit of code in ContentAutofillRouter.



This change is a no-op because BrowserAutofillManager::HidePopupImpl()

only has an effect if a popup is visible. In particular,

ChromeAutofillClient::popup_controller_ is invalidated by the first

call; so not even the metrics are affected.

entry.title: [Autofill] Move key-press handling to AutofillPopupControllerImpl
entry.content:
This CL moves the content::RenderWidgetHost::KeyPressEventCallback

from ContentAutofillDriver and ContentAutofillRouter to

AutofillPopupControllerImpl.



The main purpose is to eliminate //content dependencies in

ContentAutofillRouter. There are other options to remove this dependency

because content::RenderWidgetHost::KeyPressEventCallback is just a type

alias.



But this move also has a few other advantages:

1. Architecture: a key-press listener is not a per-RenderFrameHost

concept, but a per-RenderWidgetHost concept, and multiple RFHs may

share a RWH.

2. Simplicity: tracking the last-queried ContentAutofillDrivers in

ContentAutofillRouter is very complicated due to race conditions.

This CL is the main step to eliminate this tracking altogether.

3. Architecture: a key-press listener is not browser-renderer

communication, so it doesn't belong into ContentAutofillDriver

and ContentAutofillRouter.

entry.title: Revert "ozone/drm: Leave Link Status=Bad when a Connector Has no Modes"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a3bb1cf7641c234901a8385c4b1fcf91c493dd5c.



Reason for revert:

Querying all connectors for each modeset test and modeset introduces

a significant delay to the display configuration process, especially

during display configuration fallback in Chrome.



Revert and try to find a solution that doesn't require connector

fetching from DRM.



Original change's description:

> ozone/drm: Leave Link Status=Bad when a Connector Has no Modes

>

> Currently, Chrome always resets a connector's link status to GOOD before

> modesetting. This is important when a connector is reported by DRM to

> have some operational bandwidth and modes, since a connector that was

> previously marked in a bad state must be reset in order to successfully

> atomic commit in the future.

>

> However, if link-training fallback attempts have exhausted all possible

> bit-rate combinations and still failed to train the connector, it should

> have all its modes pruned and marked in a bad state.

>

> Chrome already prunes all connectors that are marked connected and have

> no modes [1]. This ensures that connectors that are in a bad state are

> ignored by higher layers of Chrome (e.g. Ash/Lacros) and no modeset or

> page flips are attempted on them (simply because a display abstraction

> will not not exists for the pruned connector).

>

> This patch ensures that the connectors that are ignored by Chrome are

> also left in a bad state when the other connectors are being modeset.

>

> [1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ui/ozone/platform/drm/common/drm_util.cc;l=415-418

>

entry.title: LoAF: support approximate source locations for promise resolvers
entry.content:
Attribute the source location of a promise resolver that contributed

to LoAF to the script that created it, e.g. the script that called

fetch().



Getting the exact source location of the promise resolver itself

would require capturing a stack trace, which might be too much

overhead, so this is the next best thing. We can revise in the future

whether a shallow stack trace is something we're OK with in some

circumstances.



Note that it's impossible to get the location of the actual then(),

as that's a microtask that's batched together with all the rest of

the microtasks (e.g. other then()s of the same promise).



The animation frame monitor maintains a weak map between the promise

resolver and the source location of the event

listener/script-block/callback that was responsible for creating it.

This source location is then used when a promise is resolved and the

resolution task is a long script that contributes to the LoAF.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix promo button animation glitch in Recent tabs
entry.content:
After a passphrase user signs in with the Recent Tabs promo, strange animation appears: 1) the promo slide quickly to the top of the

screen and 2) the action button changed position.



1) is due to view animation accidentally switched to YES in the middle

of the view content refresh, when the animation was intentionally

disabled.



2) is due to a wrong top margin for the action button in the

placeholder view, which takes the place of the sign-in button once the

user is signed in.



This CL fixes both glitches and is meant to be merged into M117.

handled in crbug.com/1474366
